pers, putting Cypriot commitment to the Palestinian cause at question.\nThe expulsion of two alleged Israeli spies from the island in 1998 also caused tension between the two governments.\n\nThe two countries now appear to be on improving terms, there has been coopertation on numerous areas but mostly on agriculture, military and tourism. The Cypriot government has also been reported to be making deals with both Israel and Egypt in exploring for oil off the southern Cyprus coast.\n\nIsraeli foreign minister Avigdor Lieberman visited Cyprus at the invitation of his Cypriot counterpart when Netanyahu was in Washington for the direct talks with the Palestinian leader. Lieberman and Cyprus foreign minister Kyprianou have met several times this year in an effort to strengthen relations between their countries.\nBULLET::::- Cyprus has an embassy in Tel Aviv.\nBULLET::::- Israel has an embassy in Nicosia.\nBULLET::::- Both countries are members of the Union for the Mediterranean.\nBULLET::::- Cyprus Foreign Affairs: List of bilateral treaties with Israel\n-valign=\"top\"\n1962-06\nBULLET::::- Cypriot president Makarios made a state visit to Japan in 1970. Subsequently, Cypriot president Spyros Kyprianou visited in 1984 and president George Vasiliou visited in 1989 and 1990.\nBULLET::::- The balance of trade between Cyprus and Japan is heavily weighed in favor of Japan, with Japan exporting automobiles and electrical products and importing clothing and food products.\nBULLET::::- Cyprus is represented in Japan through its non-resident ambassador based in Beijing, China, with an honorary consulate in Tokyo.\nBULLET::::- Japan is represented in Cyprus through its non-resident ambassador based in Athens, Greece, with as an honorary consulate in Limassol.\nBULLET::::- Cypriot Ministry of Foreign Affairs: list of bilateral treaties with Japan\nBULLET::::- Japanese Ministry of Foreign Affairs on relations with Cyprus\n-valign=\"top\"\n1960\nBULLET::::- Cyprus is represented in Jo